rous commitment to critical thinking, to redefine "revolution" for our times. From her home in Detroit, she reveals how hope and creativity are overcoming despair and decay within the most devastated urban communities. Her book is a manifesto for creating alternative modes of work, politics, and human interaction that will collectively constitute the next American Revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aSocial actionxHistoryx21st centuryxUnited States. 0aSocial actionzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aSocial movementsxHistoryx21st centuryxUnited States. 0aSocial movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aSustainable developmentxHistoryx21st centuryxUnited States. 0aSustainable developmentzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 4aactivist. 4aanthropologist. 4acheap oil. 4aconsumer culture. 4aconsumerism. 4aconsumption. 4adetroit michigan. 4aeasy credit. 4aeconomist. 4aenvironment. 4aenvironmentalism. 4ajustice in america. 4amanifesto. 4apolitical activism. 4apolitician. 4aprofessor. 4asocial awareness. 4asocial movement. 4asocial revolution. 4asustainable society. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aKurashige, Scott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520953390423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520953390.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles